description.html: The "angle" CSS data type represents an angle value expressed in degrees, gradians, radians, or turns. It is used, for example, in "gradient"s and in some transform functions.

description.html: The "custom-ident" CSS data type denotes an arbitrary user-defined string used as an identifier. It is case-sensitive, and certain values are forbidden in various contexts to prevent ambiguity.

description.html: The "dimension" CSS data type represents a "number" with a unit attached to it, for example 10px.
description.text: The <dimension> CSS data type represents a <number> with a unit attached to it, for example 10px.

description.html: The "filter-function" CSS data type represents a graphical effect that can change the appearance of an input image. It is used in the filter and backdrop-filter properties.
description.text: The <filter-function> CSS data type represents a graphical effect that can change the appearance of an input image. It is used in the filter and backdrop-filter properties.

description.html: The "flex" CSS data type denotes a flexible length within a grid container. It is used in grid-template-columns, grid-template-rows and other related properties.

description.html: The "frequency" CSS data type represents a frequency dimension, such as the pitch of a speaking voice. It is not currently used in any CSS properties.

description.html: The "gradient" CSS data type is a special type of "image" that consists of a progressive transition between two or more colors.
description.text: The <gradient> CSS data type is a special type of <image> that consists of a progressive transition between two or more colors.

description.html: The "ident" CSS data type denotes an arbitrary string used as an identifier.

description.html: The "image" CSS data type represents a two-dimensional image. There are two kinds of images: plain images, referenced with a "url", and dynamically-generated images, generated with "gradient" or element(). Additional CSS image functions include image(), image-set(), and cross-fade(). Images can be used with numerous CSS properties, such as background-image, border-image, content, cursor, and list-style-image.
description.text: The <image> CSS data type represents a two-dimensional image. There are two kinds of images: plain images, referenced with a <url>, and dynamically-generated images, generated with <gradient> or element(). Additional CSS image functions include image(), image-set(), and cross-fade(). Images can be used with numerous CSS properties, such as background-image, border-image, content, cursor, and list-style-image.

description.html: The "integer" CSS data type is a special type of "number" that represents a whole number, whether positive or negative. Integers can be used in numerous CSS properties, such as column-count, counter-increment, grid-column, grid-row, and z-index.
description.text: The <integer> CSS data type is a special type of <number> that represents a whole number, whether positive or negative. Integers can be used in numerous CSS properties, such as column-count, counter-increment, grid-column, grid-row, and z-index.

description.html: The "length" CSS data type represents a distance value. Lengths can be used in numerous CSS properties, such as width, height, margin, padding, border-width, font-size, and text-shadow.
description.text: The <length> CSS data type represents a distance value. Lengths can be used in numerous CSS properties, such as width, height, margin, padding, border-width, font-size, and text-shadow.

description.html: The "percentage" CSS data type represents a percentage value. It is often used to define a size as relative to an element's parent object. Numerous properties can use percentages, such as width, height, margin, padding, and font-size.
